  "output": "This is a Python async job-scraper/pipeline (no frontend/React exists — I'll skip that section and flag the actual analog: serial pagination loops that waste wall-clock the same way redundant re-renders waste render cycles). Here's what I found, grounded in the actual code:\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-73` (`Store.diff`)\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nOne SQLite round-trip *per job*, every run. With Amazon/Microsoft/Apple/Google fetchers alone returning thousands of listings (`max_pages` up to 40), this is thousands of individual `SELECT`s where one would do.\n\n**Fix:** load existing hashes once, diff in Python, then bulk-write:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(N) round-trips into 4 statements total.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n```python\ndef _compile(words): return [re.compile(...) for w in words if w]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per fetched job, so every keyword regex is **recompiled from scratch for every single job** — O(jobs × keywords) compilations instead of O(keywords).\n\n**Fix:** compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude): return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include): return False\n    ...\n```\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `fetchers.py:894` (Meta token scraper, double regex scan)\n\n```python\ntok = lambda p: (re.search(p, page) or [None, \"\"])[1] if re.search(p, page) else \"\"\n```\n\n`re.search(p, page)` runs **twice** per call — once for the ternary condition, once inside the expression — over the full careers-page HTML. Called 4× per `fetch_meta` run (lsd, rev, spin_b, spin_t) = 8 full-page scans instead of 4.\n\n**Fix:**\n```python\ndef tok(p: str) -> str:\n    m = re.search(p, page)\n    return m[1] if m else \"\"\n```\n\n## 4. Concurrency / \"serial re-render\" analog — sequential pagination for known-total sources\n\n`fetch_workday` (fetchers.py:796-820), `fetch_bytedance` (:660-677), and `fetch_phenom` (:711-733) all learn the **total result count from the very first page**, then keep fetching subsequent pages one at a time in a `while`/`for` loop, awaiting each before starting the next:\n\n```python\nwhile True:\n    data = await _get_json(client, cxs, ...)\n    ...\n    offset += page_size\n    if not postings or offset >= total or offset > 5000:\n        break\n```\n\nSince `total` is known after page 1, remaining pages are independent and can be fetched concurrently instead of serially — this is the async equivalent of an unnecessary re-render waterfall, and for large boards (Workday can page to a 5000-row cap) it's the difference between ~1 request and ~250 sequential round trips.\n\n**Fix (sketch, applies to all three):**\n```python\nfirst = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={..., \"offset\": 0}, ...)\npostings = first.get(\"jobPostings\", [])\ntotal = first.get(\"total\", len(postings))\nremaining_offsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\npages = await asyncio.gather(*(\n    _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={..., \"offset\": o}, ...)\n    for o in remaining_offsets\n))\nfor data in (first, *pages):\n    postings += data.get(\"jobPostings\", [])\n```\nBound this with a small `asyncio.Semaphore` per-source (e.g. 4-6) so you don't hammer one host — the existing global `concurrency` semaphore in `fetch_all` only limits *across sources*, not within one source's pagination.\n\n## 5. Caching opportunity — `models.py:65-69` (`content_hash` / `key` recomputed on every access)\n\n`Job.key` and `Job.content_hash` are plain `@property`, recomputed (string join + SHA-256) on every access. `Store.diff` accesses `job.key` in the SELECT, then `to_row()` recomputes both `key` and `content_hash` again for the INSERT/UPDATE. Cheap individually, but adds up across thousands of jobs × multiple accesses per run.\n\n**Fix:** since `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (slots conflict) — either add explicit `key`/`content_hash` slots and memoize manually, or simplest: compute `key`/`content_hash` once in `to_row()` and reuse that dict everywhere instead of calling the properties again separately. Low priority relative to #1/#2/#4.\n\n## 6. Memory note — `raw=j` payload retention (fetchers.py, most parsers)\n\nEvery `Job` from most fetchers (`greenhouse`, `lever`, `ashby`, `phenom`, `microsoft`, `netflix`, `workday`, …) carries the entire source JSON in `raw`. `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1142-1147`) holds **every job from every source in memory simultaneously** via `asyncio.gather` before flattening, and `raw` is only dropped later in `Job.to_row()` right before the DB write. For boards like Amazon/Microsoft/Apple (thousands of postings, `max_pages` 40), this multiplies peak memory by the size of the raw payload per job. Not a \"leak\" (process is short-lived and exits), but real peak-RSS bloat.\n\n**Fix:** either drop `raw` immediately after use (nothing currently reads it after `to_row()` strips it, based on the code shown), or make it optional/lazy — only populate `raw` when a debug flag is set.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** #1 (store N+1) and #2 (regex recompilation) are the highest-value, lowest-risk fixes — both are pure algorithmic waste with no behavior change. #4 (concurrent pagination) gives the biggest wall-clock win but touches network-facing retry/backoff logic, so test it against rate limits before shipping.\n",
